PORCINE REPRODUCTIVE AND RESPIRATORY SYNDROME - CHINA (05)
**********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Mon 20 Aug 2007
Source: Forbes.com, AFX News Ltd report [edited]
<http://www.forbes.com/afxnewslimited/feeds/afx/2007/08/20/afx4037899.html>
Local authorities may have covered up outbreaks of a disease that has
killed tens of thousands of pigs in China, the nation's chief vet
said yesterday [19 Aug 2007], but insisted there was no cause for panic.
The highly infectious blue ear pig disease has killed 68 000 pigs
across China and led to another 175 000 being slaughtered, Jia
Youling, chief veterinary officer at the Ministry of Agriculture,
told reporters.
Some Western press reports have said the number of infected pigs is
much higher than disclosed government figures, citing as evidence the
dramatic spike in pork prices in China this year [2007].
"Although there may be some cover-ups (by local authorities), it is
absolutely impossible (that) the figure could be as big as...
millions or 10 million as reported by the media," Jia said.
"Panic was caused because people didn't know (it was) blue ear
disease and had no idea how to deal with it. But it doesn't mean the
number of infected pigs is huge."
Jia said that an effective blue ear vaccine had been developed and
distributed to the regions most seriously hit, and that the spread of
the disease was now under 'preliminary control.' He said more than
100 million pigs had been vaccinated. "So far, no blue ear disease
has been found in places that have done the vaccination."
Jia said China last year [2006] had 500 million pigs, the staple meat
in most Chinese diets, in stock.
A China-based adviser to the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organisation [FAO], Guo Fusheng, told AFP that the official tally of
infected pigs was probably not accurate, but that there was little
risk to humans.
"Since in the 1980s, when the disease was found in America, Europe
and other places in the world, not a single case has been found to
have spread to human beings," Guo said. "And no other animals have
been infected by the blue ear disease except pigs."
--
